name: cis-1-methyl-2-ethylcyclopentane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason:
The basic unit here is cyclopentane, which has a melting point of approximately -94°C. Adding substituents to the basic ring structure generally increases the molecular weight and size, which can lead to higher melting points due to increased van der Waals forces. 
- A methyl group typically increases the melting point by about 5°C. 
- An ethyl group, being larger than a methyl group, typically has a more pronounced effect, increasing the melting point by about 10°C.
However, the cis- configuration of the substituents creates steric hindrance and decreases the symmetry of the molecule, which can lower the melting point compared to a more symmetrical trans- isomer. This effect may reduce the melting point by around -15°C.
Combining these effects, the prediction for the melting point adjustment would be: basic unit (-94°C) + methyl group (5°C) + ethyl group (10°C) - cis configuration (-15°C).
